title: Generally A Good Start
reviewText: I was feeling kinda down for a while, and when I started scrolling through apps, an app of the day was Reflectly. It looked cute so I tapped on it. I saw it had things to motivate your day and bring out the best in you. The challenges, questions, and goals help you rejuvenate happiness. So click I went and now I have the app. This reflection is recent, I have not even had the app for a day. But it's friendly smiles and quotes to brighten your day help a lot. Reflectly is a self - journal to reflect your days. It's probably described as a diary, but it is so much more. The app is very welldesigned too. The graphics, characters, words, and more are smoothly operated by the creators. I feel really confident that I am going to be a lot more happy in the future. Conflicts and glitches aren't a problem yet, as apprised to other reviews here. You may be wondering why I have four stars. It's because I am a beginner. I haven't unlocked all if the tools involved in the Reflectly. It has shown me what to do, but it does let you explore the world of the app. Reluctantly I like this app, and if your dealing with something you'd rather not share with other people, this is the app for you. I will update if I change something about my vote. But again, the app was a generally a good start. I can already fell my stress bleeding right out of me. So now, get Reflectly, it's a great start!

title: Limited, some bugs
reviewText: Simple, clean, beautiful interface. Limited features, some bugginess, like the welcome message blinking. You can make entries for any date up to the present, and edit entries but with multiple taps. Each entry will walk you through picking your "okness" on a slider (but it moves really fast so I gotta go back); category (work, family, relationship, education, food, traveling, friends, exercise, "other")â€”it won't save other (health??)â€”you have to type it in every time and it lumps them all together in the tracking. You can choose to write or not, add pictures or not, but if you app out real quick it often freezes and you gotta start over. Entries are only searchable by their categories + moods, no custom and no photo. AI asks a question every day, sometimes seems related to mood. There's a note section below entries and a place to add more photos below. It feels buggy and like it could vanish (no backups) and if you don't fit their categories you're screwed.

title: Good Concept, Missing Some Things
reviewText: I want to start off by saying I love the idea of the app and I understand how it is supposed to work but I don't think it was executed the correct way. I've had the app for about two weeks now and have done entries every single day and there are a few things I would want to be changed. 1) Reflectly gives you "thought invoking questions" every day in the daily entries. However, i have found that they are a bit repetitive. For example, here are two questions I got. A. "Who do you look up to? Why is that?" And, "Do you have a mentor?" Also, "what do you spend most of your time on?" And "what is the biggest waste of time in your day?" I do understand that these questions are not the same but they are just a few examples of questions I have been asked that I find myself answering the same thing to. So I guess what I would want to be different is the type of questions they ask you. 2) Reflectly does not allow you to link videos to your daily entries, however they do let you link photos. This may be because of how much storage videos take up and that may make it impossible, but if it is possible it would be nice to be able to link videos. Things I like about Reflectly1) The price. This is one thing I don't really have a problem with. I'm paying $40 for 365 days worth of online diaries. That's a good deal to me. 2) The UI. It is a pretty simple app to use and the software glitches are pretty few and far between. However, I wish it was easier to access entries you made previously. It takes a while for me to scroll to my first entry even though I've only made about 14 of them. I would like it if there was some sort of menu you could access that could allow you to scroll through previous dates to find the entry you want to find. Thank you for reading my review/wish list, I hope this helps you in your decision to devote time and/or money into this app.

title: DO NOT SIGN UP FOR THE FREE TRIAL
reviewText: I thought this would be a great tool for the new year, however I stopped using it quickly. I caught the flu and I went a couple days over the week-long trial. I understand that I should have set a reminder in my phone and that it was my error, however what really upset me was that when I tried contacting them through email and Facebook (their only options for customer service), I never even received a reply. If the creators of this app were truly focused on bringing better mental health to the masses, they should start by having a human respond to their customers. $50 may be a drop in the bucket for them since they have thousands of paying subscribers, but for me, accidentally spending $50 on an app I found to be underwhelming is almost as frustrating as realizing a company that portrays itself to be "mindful" has no option of discourse for their customers at all. This company can and should do better.

title: I really love it but...
reviewText: I really love it . However , I'm giving it four stars . Overall it is a very good app that I will be looking forward to using in the future . Now you are probably wondering why I give it four stars , it's because of the price . While yes , the price of the app use is free , you are very limited to what you can do . If you are looking to just vent into a virtual journal , then look no further , this IS the app for you . But ... if you're like me and want to take it further by taking photos and seeing progress ( like streaks and daily moods ) then you will have to buy it to access it . A premium account would be better for you if you want to go out and explore photos , get personal insights and more . The app , although , is still amazing , no glitches (yet , don't count me on it ) and runs very smoothly . If you haven't seen an ad on this , it's basically an online personal diary where you can tell about your day and describe it by clicking what made it the way you feel about it  ( such as food , travel, relationships etc. ) and your emotion( confused , happy , anxious ) . You can customize the screen and add onto the way your day was . I really like that and it's a good app worth the try . ðŸ˜Š I'll update if something happens or whatever.

That's just the writing portion of the app. Next you get "personal stats" which you have to pay for with premium. I can't really say anything about premium, because I don't have it, but I think this app is definitely worth trying! Please try it and tell your friends. title: A very good app but my account disappeared
reviewText: I had an account on Reflectly, and I used it for more than a year! It was really awesome to go back and see my entries and witness how much I had grown. I never deleted my account nor the app, but for some reason, when I opened the app, it was on the sign in page. I tried signing in with every single possible email and password, but it didn't work. I even tried, multiple times, to send a recovery password to my emails, but the email was never sent! I'm really sad because I had a lot of stories and journal entries on my account that I really love! title: THANK YOU REFLECTLY!
reviewText: I'm a freshman in high school, well, now I'm a sophomore, and if any of you have been there, you KNOW the struggle. I have lots of little mental problems that I go to a counselor for. However, I never talk about what needs to be talked about UNLESS the things I need to talk about are HAPPENING to me. I saw reflectly by chance on a YouTube ad, and thought "hey! That might help me keep track of my feelings!" So I downloaded it and I LOVE IT! I logged all my days from the past week, and tried the free trial for the + version (I'm subscribed now). I love the fact that it shows you how your improving over time! I noticed lots of helpful things that I can talk to my counselor about! I can even show her my entries, which I'm already excited to do! I have ADHD, so I often forget to do things. However, at the end of the day, I've been excited to write about my day, no matter how it went or what happened. I also really like how it has a place for daily pictures. It helps me want to get outside and take some pictures and make a day that's gonna make a cool entry! I don't know why, but reflectly is working! I've tried paper journaling before, but it just feels like I'm talking to myself, you know? Reflectly makes it feel like someone is listening to you and cares about how your day went. I found that keeps me motivated to log another day. I've been doing so much better and I feel so much less stressed now that I can wright down how my day went. The charts help me WANT to improve my attitude so I can see the improvement! The daily questions help me think and learn more about myself, too. Thank you reflectly! I will never stop using this app!

title: Had Potential; Too many requests to go Premium.
reviewText: I downloaded this as the ad looked interesting. Saw there was a free version and thought why not. I set it up and saw which options were available for free and they seemed suitable for what I'd be using it for. The limit you on your journal entries which was fine with me as I don't have the time for that every day. Except, you answer the few questions they give you and you are treated with a page telling you all the great feature of Premium... with no way to exit out of it to go back to the home page. title: It's nice for what it is
reviewText: It's a simple little journal app that just lets you jot down the days thoughts, and the app never tried to sell itself as something else, and that's the entire reason I got it. I found no bugs within the app yet which is really good, but something's that bother me a little bit about it is just the really small details. Such as the times for when you can get reminders set asking about your day and nudging users to use the app. I think it's a little weird that there's both for AM and PM, but I do get that maybe some people with the app pull night shifts so the early morning is the night for them and that's when they want to use the app. But I just think it would help if there was maybe a toggle button to select which time frame you'd want the reminders in. Also the slider bar I just find really hard to use, maybe because I have shakes hands, but when I was trying to pick my times for the reminders the bar kept moving to different times than when I wanted it. I'm sure this is mostly my fault, but I just thought maybe a scroll button, to help easier get to specific times, like intervals, would help.Also throughout a day lots of emotions can happen. Perhaps in the morning I'm really happy but in the after noon it became sad. I don't want to say my day was sad, because well, it wasn't all bad. So maybe having the option to have multiple entries into a days notebook would be a good idea. As of right now I'm just going backwards and labeling them with dates in order to keep my good mornings desperate from my bad evenings.Other wise for what the app is it's nice, it's a simple note taker that looks pretty and doesn't have millions of customization options to confused people and make them anxious when they're just trying to quickly get words out.

title: Good idea- but...
reviewText: This app seems like a great way to chart your emotions over a long period of time and reflect on your day. The problem I ran into though, was that you seemed to have to pay for everything! title: Iâ€™ve tried all the self-care apps and this is the only one that sticks!
reviewText: I absolutely love this app. Reflectly gives me a place to vent when I don't want to burden my friends and boyfriend with my problems. It helps my process my experiences and emotions and makes me feel like I've accomplished something each day. I've tried a lot of other journaling and mental health apps, but this is the only one that keeps me coming back to journal consistently. It's easy to use and doesn't overwhelm you by trying to do too much in one app. I'm also glad I got premium, because I know if I invest $ in something, I'm more likely to keep it up, plus the extra insights make it worth it. title: Journaling made easy!
reviewText: I think journaling is very therapeutic but really who has the time to sit down with a pen and paper to write about their day? Reflectly really gives me the opportunity to look back at my day and be grateful for my blessings and work on the things I'm unhappy with. The questions and prompts are helpful and really just allow you to reflect (duh!). My favorite feature is that it reminds you to take the time to just glance over your day and release whatever you were holding in. I also love that it tracks your progress. title: Love love love the app! Except..
reviewText: Ok so I love this app. It's cute, and it only takes a few minutes (2-3) each day to use. I like the daily questions and the photos you can add to your daily journal entry. All of this is great except for the subscription you have to buy for a lot of the features. Without the subscription, you are limited to 500 words per entry instead of 1250, and you cannot see your stats over time of your mood each day. There are also achievements you can get for the number of entries you have put in and a "Streaks" feature that records how many days in a row you have used Reflectly. Very cute idea though, and simple enough to not get stressed about it. Would recommend to use for a while before you are sure you want to subscribe to it.

title: Mental Health!
reviewText: Mental health is a very important thing to have in your life! Constantly keeping your emotions inside you is not ok. Sometimes you need to vent about your day, and feel someone is actually listening. That's literally exactly what Reflectly does! I am a  kid using this app. I downloaded it of a Snapchat promotion. I thought it was dumb, and didn't really work. Considering every add Snapchat has that is a game you have to pay for to actually get the thing you came for. I thought Reflectly was one of those. A little trick Snapchat tried to do to get money. It kept popping up, I finally decided to download it. I never had an app like this on my device, so I was kinda confused. It is actually a really easy app to use! May is mental health awareness month, so it was another reason I wanted it. I took baby steps at first like getting more sleep, waking up earlier, and eating breakfast. These steps would help me be more productive in school and all, but I felt they didn't really help me mentally. Reflectly has so many cool gadgets to make you be able to keep track of your emotions this is including dates, stickers, and images! They also provide questions. People do a free trial, get charged 40 something bucks for a year subscription, and then can't log on or get a refund for something they didn't pay for. Then all the responses are copied and pasted explaining that apple didn't register their upgrade and that they need to log out and log back in. For people who don't have money to spare, I recommend using the free version.
